    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Undecided and Fickle. Why Not?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan Posner letter charges that not voting is 'abdication of human identity as well as citizenship' (Oct 22 Week in Review article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Focusing on the Few, Blind to the Many'' (Week in Review, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>I have little respect for Americans who do not bother to vote. Citizens in less fortunate countries seem to realize that voting is an existential act.  Not voting is an abdication of human identity as well as citizenship.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Focusing on the Few, Blind to the Many'' (Week in Review, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>I have little respect for Americans who do not bother to vote. Citizens in less fortunate countries seem to realize that voting is an existential act.  Not voting is an abdication of human identity as well as citizenship.</p>
        <p>Even less deserving of respect are those whose abdication is based on not being sufficiently entertained by the candidates or on having actually to think before making a choice.</p>
        <p>ALAN POSNER  East Lansing, Mich., Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
